The paper deals with the problem of leader election in distributed networks, which is a classic problem in distributed computing (cs.DC). The focus of the paper is on the message complexity of the algorithm, which is a key aspect of distributed computing and falls under the category of distributed systems (cs.DS). The paper also discusses the connectivity of the network graph and its impact on the algorithm's performance, which is related to the field of network science and social networks (cs.SI). The paper uses concepts from probability theory and graph theory, which are also relevant to information theory (cs.IT). Finally, the paper presents lower bounds for leader election, which is a topic in network information theory (cs.NI).
